HEADWORD: Renovate
<hw>Ren"o*vate</hw> <pr>(r?n"?-v?t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>renovatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>renovare</ets>;pref. <ets>re-</ets>
re- + <ets>novare</ets> to make new, fr. <ets>novus</ets> new. See
<er>New</er>, and <?/<?/ <er>Renew</er>.]</ety> <def>To make over again;
to restore to freshness or vigor; to renew.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All nature feels the <qex>reniovating</qex> force⟦br⟧
Of winter.</q> <rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

